Let me assure you, even something you might think is as "simple" as legal aid is a matter of life and death. We help homeless victims of sexual assault and domestic violence, and people who's wages have been stolen and disability denied. Legal aid saves lives every day

Almost a million Americans have died of COVID, but they sent out some $600 checks and told us to get our asses back to work. And I'm not even getting into the underlying racism of who we're aiding and who we're sacrificing.

Where the fuck was this money in 2020 when the pandemic started? Why can't they send Ukraine 6 billion instead, so they don't sacrifice the lives of the poorest Americans in the process of providing aid. You don't buy lives with other lives.

@EmberFirehair Seriously, they could both write a check tomorrow (ok not really because funds of that size are basically imaginary, but you know what I mean.) I'm sure the military could spare some cash. Maybe from the fund they use to buy tanks to be used on US citizens.

I want to be clear that I support aid to the Ukraine. I'm not an isolationist and I believe that the US should contribute in world crisis. But let's be honest - the US is in a world crisis itself, but congress couldn't be fucking bothered to aid its own citizens.

My agency does nothing but legal aid - we serve the low income residents of Washington at no cost to them. Due to this massive cut in the funding originally anticipated, we're looking at possible layoffs and losing staff that neither we, or Washington state can afford to lose.

In case you're wondering just where the US is finding the money to run Ukraine that 13 billion dollar check, I can confirm it's being taken from programs meant to serve the poorest and most marginalized people in the US. Expected funds for legal aid were slashed in half.

@POCGamer Yes, I think this hits the nail on the head - most Americans and most American media doesn't delve into the wider world fallout and just what was meant by "lost generation." Most people don't know just how astronomically high the death toll was in WWI.

@POCGamer But this series does an incredible job of dealing with the experiences of those in the war as well as the world afterwards. Incredibly compelling and highly unexpected after watching the TV show.

@POCGamer I became fascinated by WWI when I was a teenager reading the last book in the Anne of Green Gables series. The last book takes place over the span of the war, and while it's very poetically written, it very much conveys the grief and fear of being at the home front.
The conversation takes place in Paris in 1918, right after the "Great War", but it hits way too close to home in 2022.

Second pro-tip: If a portable AC unit has only one hose, it's not worth the money. Look for one with two hoses - they're going to run you $400-500 because they actually work. Yes even when it was 108 F outside. Mine kept me from having to get a hotel room last year.

I want to share an insurance pro-tip before we slide into summer: you can use your FSA to pay for an air conditioner if you have a letter of medical necessity. If you're someone who has a medical condition that's worse by heat, I HIGHLY recommend looking at a portable AC unit.

A good massage therapist will always ask you if the pressure is ok for you. Don't be shy or worried about offending them, it's your body and they don't know how things feel to you. It's also a good idea to mention you've never had one before.

If you've never had a massage and would like to try one, I recommend starting with a Swedish or "relaxation" massage. Deep tissue or sports massages should wait until you have more experience with them and what works for your body. Also never be afraid to ask for less pressure.
Extra bonus: she did not expect me to make small talk, bless her. Small talk gets old quickly, especially when you're trying to relax/getting your knots turbo kneaded out of existence.

@yeloson Oh god I feel that in my soul. And of course because you're a cancer survivor everyone is always on slightly higher alert. (Which is both good and bad.)

So while I know that the chances of recurrence goes down every year, it never goes away and you're always going to be aware of it. I think that's why I have mixed feelings about hitting the ten year mark. Plus the '20s have been a goddamn mess, and that makes me nervous.
@yeloson Yes! And the way time has been moving since 2020 makes it even weirder. I just saw a YouTuber who was diagnosed with breast cancer and it really brought it back.

And I think it's more accurate to say "in remission", because you're never really cancer free once you've had it. Talk about things living in your head rent free? When cancer lives in your head, you pay IT rent. Cancer is with you forever, like your shadow.

One thing he never said was that I was "cancer free" as some people put it. My doctor was very blunt, in a way that I've come to appreciate over the years. I knew he wasn't sugar coating anything - when he said something had a good outcome he really meant it.

It feels weird that I never remember the "anniversary", but it's an incredibly vague date. According to my original oncologist, you're considered "in remission" starting after you completed your last treatment. I finished radiation in December of 2011.
It just occurred to me that December was the 10 year mark on my cancer remission. I have really mixed feelings about that.

And no you're not a special person who can only get [insert hours of sleep here] and be fine! You need 7 hours of sleep, I don't give a shit what capitalism has taught you! YOU NEED SEVEN+ HOURS OF SLEEP A NIGHT TO BE YOUR MOST EFFECTIVE SELF!!

I cannot properly express the difference in tiredness between getting 6 hours of sleep and crossing over that 7 hour mark. Seriously that one hour makes a huge difference! Whenever you can, please try to get 7+ hours of sleep a night, it's the minimum we need as humans.

Lol I got distracted. Anyway the point of that extremely boring thread is that my life is a farce and I spend my time catering to a tiny dictator, a cranky elderly prima donna, and a giant cryptid who thinks he's a kitten. It's boring and stupid and I (mostly) love it.

At 8 Gigi and Figment get their second dose of meds and their treats and usually food. The chaos/peace cycle continues until 10 pm when Darwin gets another cup of kibble and then we have to separate them at night so Darwin stays upstairs with us, and the girls sleep downstairs.
@noveldevice Oh it's no problem, I would try pretty much anything at this point! Sadly I'm pretty sure Gigi would still want to use them as a wading pool because she lives to torment me 😆😂

At 2 pm he gets a bowl of kibble. After that he either sacks out on our bed for 4 hours or goes back to cryptid mode. Gigi spends the day either a) lying in Erin's desk chair, b) running around aimlessly and then whining at Erin until he lets her into the bedroom, or sleeping.
Sometimes he leaves her alone, sometimes he decides he wants to "play" and then he chases her. She screams at him and hides under our dresser until I lock him back out of the bedroom.

He wants kibble. He ALWAYS wants kibble. My life is spent feeding a small dictator while protecting her food from a large cryptid. At some point Figment will wake Darwin exists and will yell and hiss about it on her way to the food.

She attacks her brother and makes noises like a rubber chicken with emphysema if he starts to win the wrestling match. He's 22 lbs, he ALWAYS wins. Now Darwin will either be a calm angel who falls asleep for the whole day, or a restless cryptid who runs around the house all day.

Gigi always wants to first run around all over when she wakes up, then she wants to eat and take a short nap. Then it's time to play "drive her parents nuts for the next 8 hours." She whines when she's hungry and she's always hungry. She whines when she can't be in our offices.

Darwin goes downstairs where he gets his first container of wet food for the day. Gigi and Figment get some kibble and then Figment goes to lay down in her heated bed for the rest of the day. Darwin has to be kept out of our room so he doesn't snipe their food.

We (should) remove the pillows that we keep stuffed under the gate to keep Gigi from crawling under it. Gigi and Figment come upstairs where they both get a pill pocket and two crunchy treats. (I'm not kidding, this is an exact thing and they will whine if they don't get them.)

Lemme walk you through a day in the Darwin and Lovelace household, because this place sure as shit doesn't belong to Erin and I. The morning starts at 8 am when we open the pet gate that we use to keep Darwin upstairs at night.

We switched to all kitty fountains for the cats because a few months ago Gigi decided that any vessel with water in it is a wading pool and she makes a massive mess. So now we have Gigi who can't be trusted with a bowl of water, and Darwin who won't drink out of a fountain. https://t.co/mo8qtbWFvx

@EmberFirehair Yeah, it's definitely a problem that intersects class as much as weight. My husband's family is poor and from Kentucky, so he didn't have any of those advantages either, but he certainly has the benefit of being a cis white dude.
@leighfromcanada I was very much NOT asking for advice in this thread, and if I wanted it I would not be asking a random stranger from a different country about my options. Learn to read the room.

Black people have systematically and intentionally been denied all of these advantages, and taught over and over again that we don't deserve them. Don't want to get uppity, right? But yeah, actually I WANT to get uppity, but there's no one to show me how.

I don't have any of this knowledge, I barely even know where to look, and I'm afraid to talk about it because I feel guilty every day for being more economically successful than many of my peers. Ugh, just typing that makes me feel gross!

Not nearly as much as Shelly from next door who's parents gave her a down payment on a house for a wedding present and they're only 10 years from paying it off. This means more time to save, to build credit, to learn ways to keep and grow your money.

Just having parents to help you with a downpayment on your house is a MASSIVE advantage that I'm sure tons of people don't even think about. I'm 41. I'm hoping to buy a house within the next two years. How much time to I have to pay it off and build equity before I retire?

When you achieve a modicum of financial success, you're more vulnerable than your white peers because of this lack of knowledge. There might be someone with my exact same age and job out there, but if she's white and grew up middle class she could have so many more advantages.
I don't know how to plan for retirement, buy a house, start a savings, hire people to work for me in any kind of capacity and a bunch of other stuff I don't even realize is out there.

And trust me, I'm happy with that! That is a level of success that feels stunning to me. But it also means I don't know how to find good and services that would really improve the quality of my life because I've never met someone with regular access to those things.

I mean don't get me wrong, if Erin lost his job tomorrow we'd still be screwed and quickly because he makes more money than me (surprising no one), but it would take longer than one month for us to get behind on rent, and that's the highest form of success I know.

One of the things the lack of generational wealth does is leave Black people unprepared to use resources that other people at their income level take for granted. For the first time in my entire 41 years I am not living paycheck to paycheck and it's honestly confusing.

Once people get over the initial awkwardness, the answers you get are often really fascinating or hilarious. You might have someone who doesn't know how to swim, or you might have someone who's random fact was that they had recently had a heart attack. (True story.)

Having lead a ludicrous number of new hire orientations in my life, I have become very adept at drawing people out for dumb ice breakers. My go to favorite is to ask people to share a random or interesting fact about themselves, since it gives people a choice of what to share.

All that is to say I think it's time to re-examine our definitions of failure (and success, but that's another thread)  and work on enjoying the experience and the attempt, even if we don't continue with plans.

Sure I'm out some money, but that money went to having a cool experience, and I can probably sell the equipment to another beekeeper. None of that is failure. And there's every chance I'll love it and spend the rest of my life cooing maternally over furry bugs.

Yes, it's on me to make sure that if I do start a hive I treat it responsibly, whether that be continuing to care for it, or finding a beekeeper who can. Yes, I will have spent time and money,  but neither is wasted, and it's pretty awful to consider that failure.

Even with the beekeeping - I'm excited for it, studying for it, and planning for it, but there's a  reasonable chance that I won't bring it to fruition, or I won't like it at all. I still had the experience and I still gain knowledge.

Not to mention having easily 4 or 5 years of black worry and ivy removed from the backyard, as well as having all of my beds and borders mulched (except for the veggie patch.) I even raised some petunias that I swear would have won prizes. But somehow I have no follow through?

I transformed an overgrown, neglected, ugly ass yard full of dead grass and weeds into the start of a truly spectacular urban garden with a lawn that uses native plants and supports pollinators, rhododendrons I personally nursed back to health and even a small rose garden.

I've ordered a ton of plants for next year's garden, but for some reason I feel like I'm being way too ambitious and I'll never do the necessary follow through. Which is patently ABSURD when I think about how much work and commitment I've put into our garden this year.

If there's no negative outcome, how does that count as failure? Who decides what a negative outcome is? Why does the experience gained in the attempt count for nothing? It's reached the point that even when I do complete things successfully I continue to doubt myself.

So what if I decide I don't like a project I'm working on and don't want to finish it? Or that I realize I'm not having fun with an activity and don't want to keep doing it? And honestly so what if plans I make fall through for, does that mean I shouldn't make them?

I've been thinking about the way we equate quitting with failure. I've gotten to the point where I'm afraid to make plans for the future or take up new projects because of fear that I won't be able to complete them. And really... So what if I can't complete them?
